demo 


Let's build a complete, hands-on project to see exactly how ArgoCD acts.
Since ArgoCD sits inside a Kubernetes cluster, we will use an architecture where your cluster dynamically pulls configurations directly from your GitHub repository https://github.com/mukeshdas088/my-gitops-demo.
1. The Repository Architecture from Scratch
Inside your repository (my-gitops-demo), you need to create a folder structure to house your Kubernetes declarations. We will place everything inside a folder called apps/ to keep it clean.
Your GitHub repository structure will look like this:
Plaintext
my-gitops-demo/
└── apps/
    ├── deployment.yaml      <-- [Desired State: The Python App]
    └── service.yaml         <-- [Desired State: Internal Network Map]
File A: apps/deployment.yaml
This defines the application you want running. Let's declare that we want exactly 2 replicas of an NGINX web app container.
YAML

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-python-web-app
  namespace: prod-apps
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: web-server
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: web-server
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: web-container
        image: nginx:alpine
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80

File B: apps/service.yaml
This exposes your application containers internally inside the cluster.
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: web-service
  namespace: prod-apps
spec:
  selector:
    app: web-server
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 80
  type: ClusterIP

Commit and push these two files to your main branch on GitHub before moving to the installation phase.

2. Installing ArgoCD in Your Kubernetes Cluster
Run these commands from your terminal where you have administrative kubectl access to your Kubernetes cluster.

Step 1: Create the System Namespace
Bash
kubectl create namespace argocd
Step 2: Install ArgoCD Components
This downloads and applies all the core machinery (CRDs, controllers, and network policies) that make ArgoCD run inside your cluster.
Bash
kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml
Step 3: Access the ArgoCD Web Interface
By default, the ArgoCD API server is not exposed externally. Use port-forwarding to open it locally:
Bash
kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443
You can now open your web browser and go to https://localhost:8080.
Step 4: Retrieve the Automated Password
To log in (username: admin), retrieve the auto-generated initial secret using this command:
Bash
kubectl -n argocd get secret argocd-initial-admin-secret -o jsonpath="{.data.password}" | base64 -d; echo
3. The ArgoCD Application Blueprint (Connecting Git to Cluster)
Now we must tell ArgoCD to track your specific GitHub repository. We do this by creating an ArgoCD Application Custom Resource inside the cluster.
Create a local file named argocd-app-root.yaml and run kubectl apply -f argocd-app-root.yaml:
YAML

apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: my-gitops-application
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default
  source:
    # 1. Point to Mukesh's GitHub Repository
    repoURL: 'https://github.com/mukeshdas088/my-gitops-demo.git'
    targetRevision: HEAD
    path: apps  # The folder inside the repo where our YAMLs live
  destination:
    # 2. Point to the destination Cluster and Namespace
    server: 'https://kubernetes.default.svc'
    namespace: prod-apps
  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true      # Automatically delete resources if they are deleted from Git
      selfHeal: true   # Override manual human interventions automatically!
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true # Create the 'prod-apps' namespace if it doesn't exist

4. Witnessing GitOps in Action (The Experiments)
Once you apply the root application manifest, look at your ArgoCD UI or run kubectl get pods -n prod-apps. You will see your 2 app containers spin up instantly.
Here is exactly how it acts under two different scenarios:
Experiment 1: Testing Automated Synchronization (Scale Up)
Go to your local machine, open apps/deployment.yaml, and change replicas: 2 to replicas: 5.
Commit and push the code: git commit -am "Scale replicas to 5" && git push.
Watch the ArgoCD Dashboard or run kubectl get pods -n prod-apps -w.
What happens: Within seconds, without any human touching a terminal or runner executing deployment scripts, ArgoCD notices the mismatch between your Git repo and your live cluster. It instantly spins up 3 new pods to match your desired count of 5.
Experiment 2: Testing Self-Healing (Simulating Human Error)
Let's pretend a manual operator bypasses Git and tries to run an unauthorized command directly in production.
Run this command to manually delete your service:
Bash
kubectl delete service web-service -n prod-apps
What happens: Within moments, ArgoCD detects that the live state is missing the service, but your my-gitops-demo GitHub repository says it should exist. ArgoCD immediately overrides the deletion and recreates the service automatically.

